{{tmbox|type=notice|text='''Please help <u>''improve''</u> Wikibooks'''.

Your [[Special:Contributions/162.235.248.20|recent edits]]{{ #if:  |, such as those you made to [[:]],|}} are considered unconstructive by fellow contributors. Please read [[WB:WIW|What is Wikibooks?]] for a description of what we allow. You can ask questions or ask for help in the [[WB:HELP|Assistance Reading Room]]. Please use the [[Wikibooks:Sandbox|sandbox]] for experimenting with the wiki software in the future.<br>Thanks. '''''[[User:Curtaintoad|<span style="color:red;background:blue;font-family:Curtaintoad">~ curtaintoad ~</span>]][[User talk:Curtaintoad|<span style="color:blue;background:red;font-family:Curtaintoad">~ talk ~</span>]]''''' 00:50, 23 September 2013 (UTC)
}}

This is a glossary that contains terms related to programming in the context of Lua. Its use is recommended to find the meaning of words that are not understood.

; abstract class {{anchor|abstract class}}
: An [[w:concrete class#Abstract and concrete|abstract class]] is a class of which instances cannot be created directly. Abstract classes are [[#abstract type|abstract types]].
; abstract data type {{anchor|abstract data type}}
: An [[w:abstract data type|abstract data type]] is a model to represent a class of [[#data structure|data structures]] that have similar behavior. Abstract data types are defined by the operations that can be performed on them and by mathematical constraints of these operations rather than by the implementation and the way the data is stored in the memory of the computer.
; abstract type {{anchor|abstract type}}
: An [[w:abstract type|abstract type]] is a type of data of which instances cannot be created directly.
; actual parameter {{anchor|actual parameter}}
: See [[#argument|argument]].
; additive inverse {{anchor|additive inverse}}
: The [[w:additive inverse|additive inverse]] of a number is the number that, when added to that number, yields zero. For example, the additive inverse of 42 is -42.
; arithmetic negation {{anchor|arithmetic negation}}
: Arithmetic negation is the operation that produces the [[#additive inverse|additive inverse]] of a number.
; arithmetic operation {{anchor|arithmetic operation}}
: An [[w:arithmetic operation|arithmetic operation]] is an operation whose operands are numbers.
; arity {{anchor|arity}}
: The [[w:arity|arity]] of an operation or of a function is the number of operands or arguments the operation or function accepts.
; argument {{anchor|argument}}
: An [[w:parameter (computer programming)|argument]] is a value passed to a [[#function|function]].
; array {{anchor|array}}
: An [[w:array data structure|array]] is a [[#data structure|data structure]] consisting of a collection of values, each identified by at least one array index or key.
; associative array {{anchor|associative array}}
: An [[w:associative array|associative array]] is an [[#abstract data type|abstract data type]] composed of a collection of pairs of keys and values, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
; binary operation {{anchor|binary operation}}
: A [[w:binary operation|binary operation]] is an operation of which the arity is two.
; boolean {{anchor|boolean}}
: See [[#logical data|logical data]].
; boolean negation {{anchor|boolean negation}}
: See [[#logical negation|logical negation]].
; chunk {{anchor|chunk}}
: A chunk is a sequence of statements.
; concatenation {{anchor|concatenation}}
: [[w:String concatenation|String concatenation]] is the operation of joining two strings of characters. For example, the concatenation of "snow" and "ball" is "snowball".
; concrete class {{anchor|concrete class}}
: A concrete class is a class of which instances can be created directly. Concrete classes are [[#concrete type|concrete types]].
; concrete type {{anchor|concrete type}}
: A concrete type is a type of which instances can be created directly.
; condition {{anchor|condition}}
: A condition is a [[#predicate|predicate]] that is used in a [[#conditional statement|conditional statement]] or as an operand to the [[#conditional operator|conditional operator]]. Conditions, in Lua, are considered as true when their expression evaluates to a value other than <code>nil</code> or <code>false</code>, and are considered as false otherwise.
; conditional operator {{anchor|conditional operator}}
: A [[w:conditional operator|conditional operator]] is an operator that returns a value if a [[#condition|condition]] is true and another if it isn't.
; conditional statement {{anchor|conditional statement}}
: A [[w:conditional (computer programming)|conditional statement]] is a statement that executes a piece of code if a [[#condition|condition]] is true.
; data structure {{anchor|data structure}}
: A [[w:data structure|data structure]] is a particular way of storing and organizing data in the memory of a computer. It is the implementation of an [[#abstract data type|abstract data type]].
; data type {{anchor|data type}}
: A [[w:data type|data type]] is a model for representing the storage of data in the memory of a computer.
; dictionary {{anchor|dictionary}}
: See [[#associative array|associative array]].
; exclusive disjunction {{anchor|exclusive disjunction}}
: [[File:Venn0110.svg|110px|thumb|[[w:Venn diagram|Venn diagram]] of <math>\scriptstyle a \veebar b</math>]]The [[w:exclusive or|exclusive disjunction]] operation is a [[#binary operation|binary operation]] that produces the value <code>true</code> when one of its operands is true but the other is not. The exclusive disjunction of <var>a</var> and <var>b</var> is expressed mathematically as <math>\scriptstyle a \veebar b</math>. There is no operator corresponding to exclusive disjunction in Lua, but <math>\scriptstyle a \veebar b</math> can be represented as <code>(a or b) and not (a and b)</code>.
; formal parameter {{anchor|formal parameter}}
: See [[#parameter|parameter]].
; function {{anchor|function}}
: A function is a sequence of statements (instructions) that perform a specific task. Functions can be used in a program wherever that particular task needs to be performed. Functions are usually defined in the program that will use them, but are sometimes defined in libraries that can be used by other programs.
; hash map {{anchor|hash map}}
: See [[#hash table|hash table]].
; hash table {{anchor|hash table}}
: A [[w:hash table|hash table]] is an implementation as a [[#data structure|data structure]] of the [[#associative array|associative array]]. A hash table uses a [[w:hash function|hash function]] to compute an index into an array of buckets or slots, from which the value corresponding to the index can be found.
; inline if {{anchor|inline if}}
: See [[#conditional operator|conditional operator]].
; integer {{anchor|integer}}
: An [[w:integer|integer]] is a number that can be written without a fractional or decimal component. Integers are implemented in Lua in the same way as other numbers.
; length operation {{anchor|length operation}}
: The length operation is the operation that produces the number of values in an array.
; literal {{anchor|literal}}
: A literal is a notation for representing a fixed value in source code. All values can be represented as literals in Lua except threads and userdata.
; logical complement {{anchor|logical complement}}
: The [[w:logical complement|logical complement]] of a boolean value is the boolean value that is not that value. This means the logical complement of <code>true</code> is <code>false</code> and vice versa.
; logical conjunction {{anchor|logical conjunction}}
: [[File:Venn0001.svg|110px|thumb|Venn diagram of <math>\scriptstyle a \and b</math>]]The [[w:logical conjunction|logical conjunction]] operation is a [[#binary operation|binary operation]] that produces the value <code>true</code> when both of its operands are true and <code>false</code> in all other cases. It is implemented as the <code>and</code> operator in Lua and it returns its first operand if it is <code>false</code> or <code>nil</code> and the second operand otherwise. The logical conjunction of <var>a</var> and <var>b</var> is expressed mathematically as <math>\scriptstyle a \and b</math>.
; logical data {{anchor|logical data|logical data type}}
: The [[w:logical data type|logical data type]], which is generally called the boolean type, is the type of the values <code>false</code> and <code>true</code>.
; logical disjunction {{anchor|logical disjunction}}
: [[File:Venn0111.svg|110px|thumb|Venn diagram of <math>\scriptstyle a \or b</math>]]The [[w:logical disjunction|logical disjunction]] operation is a [[#binary operation|binary operation]] that produces the value <code>false</code> when both of its operands are false and <code>true</code> in all other cases. It is implemented as the <code>or</code> operator in Lua and it returns the first operand if it is neither <code>false</code> nor <code>nil</code> and the second otherwise. The logical disjunction of <var>a</var> and <var>b</var> is expressed mathematically as <math>\scriptstyle a \or b</math>.
; logical negation {{anchor|logical negation}}
: [[w:Logical negation|Logical negation]], implemented in Lua by the <code>not</code> operator, is the operation that produces the [[#logical complement|logical complement]] of a boolean value.
; map {{anchor|map}}
: See [[#associative array|associative array]].
; method {{anchor|method}}
: A [[w:method (computer programming)|method]] is a function that is a member of an object and generally operates on that object.
; modulo {{anchor|modulo}}
: See [[#modulo operation|modulo operation]].
; modulo operation {{anchor|modulo operation}}
: The [[w:modulo operation|modulo operation]], implemented in Lua by the <code>%</code> operator, is the operation that produces the remainder of the division of a number by another.
; modulus {{anchor|modulus}}
: See [[#modulo operation|modulo operation]].
; nil {{anchor|nil}}
: The type nil is the type of the value <code>nil</code>, whose main property is to be different from any other value; it usually represents the absence of a useful value.
; not operator {{anchor|not operator}}
: See [[#logical negation|logical negation]].
; number {{anchor|number}}
: The number type represents real ([[w:double-precision floating-point|double-precision floating-point]]) numbers. It is possible to build Lua interpreters that use other internal representations for numbers, such as single-precision float or long integers.
; operator {{anchor|operator}}
: An [[w:operator (computer programming)|operator]] is a token that generates a value from one or many operands.
; predicate {{anchor|predicate}}
; parameter {{anchor|parameter}}
: A [[w:parameter (computer programming)|parameter]] is a variable in a function definition to which the argument that corresponds to it in a call to that function is assigned.
: A predicate is an expression that evaluates to a piece of [[#logical data|logical data]].
; procedure {{anchor|procedure}}
: See [[#function|function]].
; relational operator {{anchor|relational operator}}
: A [[w:relational operator|relational operator]] is an operator that is used to compare values.
; routine {{anchor|routine}}
: See [[#function|function]].
; sign change {{anchor|sign change}}
: See [[#arithmetic negation|arithmetic negation]].
; string {{anchor|string}}
: The type string represents arrays of characters. Lua is 8-bit clean: strings can contain any 8-bit character, including embedded zeros.
; string literal {{anchor|string literal}}
: A [[w:string literal|string literal]] is the representation of a string value within the source code of a computer program. With respect to syntax, a string literal is an expression that evaluates to a string.
; subprogram {{anchor|subprogram}}
: See [[#function|function]].
; subroutine {{anchor|subroutine}}
: See [[#function|function]].
; symbol {{anchor|symbol}}
: See [[#token|token]].
; symbol table {{anchor|symbol table}}
: A [[w:symbol table|symbol table]] is an implementation as a [[#data structure|data structure]] of the [[#associative array|associative array]]. They are commonly implemented as [[#hash table|hash tables]].
; token {{anchor|token}}
: A token is an atomic piece of data, such as a word in a human language or such as a keyword in a programming language, for which a meaning may be inferred during parsing.
; variable {{anchor|variable}}
: A [[w:variable (computer science)|variable]] is a label associated to a location in the memory. The data in that location can be changed and the variable will point to the new data.
; variadic function {{anchor|variadic function}}
: A [[w:variadic function|variadic function]] is a function of indefinite arity.

